          {
            "commit": "43c01b9d94e783295edc2d1432ed3af0076a0e51",
            "subject": "LU-731 ldlm: revise and export ldlm_lock_set_data"
          }
        ],
        "author": {
          "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
          "email": "jay@whamcloud.com",
          "date": "2011-08-19 23:44:50.000000000",
          "tz": -420
        },
        "committer": {
          "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
          "email": "jay@whamcloud.com",
          "date": "2011-10-12 20:06:21.000000000",
          "tz": -420
        },
        "subject": "ORNL-10: Basic IR implementation",
        "message": "ORNL-10: Basic IR implementation\n\nTo support imperative recovery, there is a target status table defined for\neach file system defined on the MGS. When a target registers itself to the\nMGS, the MGS will change this table correspondingly.\n\nIn the status table, one important field is target NID. This NID information\nis used by clients locating server where target lives. By transferring this NID\nto clients, clients can know the restarting of targets earlier. This is\nso-called imperative recovery - the MGS notifies clients to do recovery\nimperatively instead of timeout based standard recovery.\n\nTo implement imperative recovery, clients are asked to cache a NID table, which\ncontains the location information of all servers. Clients need to hold a read\nmode ldlm plain lock - recover lock - to cache this table. Whenever the MGS\nwants to change this table, it will enqueue an EXCL recover lock so that all\nclients will be notified for this change. Clients will request for a new read\nrecover lock and then query for the MGS for NID table updates.\n\nChange-Id: I3b38ba142b810df507805b71972feeb1bade1ac2\nSigned-off-by: Jinshan Xiong <jay@whamcloud.com>\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/master"
    }
  },
